# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1930-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1930-world-series/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It played in the National Association league in 1875 and in the National League from 1876 to 1877.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] After a scandal over game-fixing, combined with financial problems, the St Louis Brown Stockings left the National League but continued to play as an independent team from 1878 to 1881.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Chris von der Ahe, a German immigrant, purchased the team prior to the 1882 season and joined the new American Association.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings posted a 37-43 game record in their first season in the American Association, giving them fifth place.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played at the Grand Avenue Grounds (which was later renamed Sportsman's Park) at the corner of Grand Avenue and Dodier Street in north St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Before the 1882 season, Von der Ahe secured a place for the team in the American Association and provided funds to bring players to St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Between 1882 and 1892, the team he built went on to win four American Association titles.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Al Spink, the team advisor, recommended Von der Ahe sign Charlie Comiskey.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Comiskey, who later played with the Chicago White Sox, was a skilled, young, first baseman who had been playing in Dubuque, Iowa.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Ned Cuthbert was a former professional player in St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Although he had retired from baseball and worked as a bartender in St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, Cuthbert remained prominent in the local baseball community.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He had encouraged Von der Ahe to purchase the team.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Von der Ahe hired Cuthbert to be his first captain, with all the duties of a field manager.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Cuthbert used his experience to attract several players to St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Most of the first-year Browns originated in St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, including brothers Jack and Bill Gleason, pitcher Jumbo McGinnis, outfielder George Seward, and catcher Tom Sullivan.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In 1866, Gus Solari laid out a professional baseball field at Sportsman's Park, St Louis.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Sixteen years later, on May 2, 1882, the opening day of the St.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings' 1882 season took place.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Approximately 2,000 spectators watched the game for a fee of one quarter each.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played numerous local teams in April exhibitions.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] McGinnis was the first pitcher and he started 45 of the team's 80 games.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It was a lead off single in the first innings.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He also scored the first run on Comiskey's three-base hit.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team won their first game with a score of 9 runs to 7.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In late May 1882, the team was in a tie for first place in its six-team league.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They were eight games over .500, putting them one game behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] There followed a seven-week period when the team lost sixteen more games than they won.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They could not contend for the championship.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] During the season, more than 175,000 spectators attended the team's games.
[src:1930-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The favorite players on the team were Comiskey and McGinnis.
[src:1930-world-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's second season in St.
[src:1930-world-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri and its second season in the American Association.
[src:1930-world-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 65–33 during the season and finished second in the American Association.
[src:1930-world-series/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's third season in St.
[src:1930-world-series/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and its third season in the American Association.
[src:1930-world-series/1884-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 67–40 during the season and finished fourth in the American Association.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's fourth season in St.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and the fourth season in the American Association.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 79–33 during the season, best in the American Association, and won their first AA pennant.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] In the World Series, the Browns played the National League champion Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The series ended in dispute, with each club winning 3 games with 1 tie.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Manager Charlie Comiskey finally was able to assemble and direct a team from start to finish the way he wanted.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The team was built on daring baserunning, clutch hitting, and the best pitching in the league.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The team as a whole led the league in both earned run average (ERA) and overall runs allowed by a healthy margin over second-best Louisville.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Individually, Dave Foutz was outstanding, as he won 33 of the 46 games he started and ranked fifth in ERA.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] His teammate Bob Caruthers was even better, compiling league-leading totals in wins (40), ERA (2.07) and winning percentage (a stellar .755).
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns took over first place to stay in the second week of May, but they made a joke of the race in July.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] On successive home stands, they had winning streaks of 17 and 12 games, combining for a major-league record 27-game winning streak at home that still stands as the best ever.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-st-louis-browns-season] They finished games laps ahead of the second-place Cincinnati Red Stockings and earned a berth in the World Series against the National League champion Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] The **1885 World Series** (the "**World's Championship**") was an end-of-the-year playoff series between the National League champion Chicago White Stockings and American Association champion St.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] The Series was played in four cities (Chicago, St.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] Game forfeited to Chicago with 1 out in the top of the 6th inning.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] With Chicago leading 5–4 in the sixth inning, Browns manager Charles Comiskey called his team off the field to protest a ruling made by umpire Dave Sullivan.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] The fifth game was played at Pittsburgh.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] The weather was cold and not over 500 people were present.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] Chicago won easily (9–2) through superior batting and fielding.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] At the end of the seventh inning, the game was called on account of darkness.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] Friday, October 23, American Park, Cincinnati — The series moved from Pittsburgh to Cincinnati‚ setting a record for most host cities in a World Series.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] (The 1887 series was later staged in 10 cities.) Chicago took a 3–2 series lead by beating the Browns 9–2.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] Louis defeated Chicago 13–4 in the 7th and final game.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] The Browns claim the game 2 forfeit didn't count and therefore claim the championship.
[src:1930-world-series/1885-world-series] There were five originally planned games to be played after Game 7; in Baltimore on the 27th, Philadelphia the 28th and 29th, and Brooklyn the 30th and 31st.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The **1930 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball for the 1930 season.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The 27th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that pitted the American League (AL) champion (and defending World Series champion) Philadelphia Athletics against the National League (NL) champion St.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The Athletics defeated the Cardinals in six games to win their fifth championship.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Philadelphia's pitching ace Lefty Grove, and George Earnshaw, the No.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] 2 man in Mack's rotation, won two games apiece.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Earnshaw also pitched seven scoreless innings as the Game 5 starter, but ended up with a no-decision as Grove relieved him in the eighth and took the win on Jimmie Foxx's two-run homer in the top of the ninth for the game's only scoring.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The Cardinals led the National League in runs scored and averaged six runs per game in the regular season, but could manage only two runs per game in this World Series.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Their win this year tied them with the Boston Red Sox for most World Series wins as of that point (five) until 1937, when the New York Yankees surged ahead of both in World Series wins and have gone on to amass 27 World Series championships as of 2026.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The city of Philadelphia would have to wait 50 years until its next World Series championship, when the Phillies became the last of the "Original Sixteen" MLB franchises to win a World Series.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] This World Series also marks the beginning of the Cardinals run of dominance in the National League in the early 1930s.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] They would win the pennant three times between 1930 and 1934 and the World Series in 1931 and '34.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] This would also be the final World Series where both teams uniforms did not have numbers.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The A's managed only five hits off of Grimes in Game 1, but all were for extra bases and each produced a run in five different innings.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Al Simmons and Mickey Cochrane hit solo home runs for the A's, helping Lefty Grove to a 5–2 win.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The A's struck first in the bottom of the second when Jimmie Foxx tripled and scored on Bing Miller's sacrifice fly.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The Cardinals loaded the bases in the third on three straight leadoff singles, then Taylor Douthit's lineout and Sparky Adams's sacrifice fly scored a run each.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Simmons's home run in the fourth tied the game.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] In the sixth, Max Bishop walked with one out and scored on Jimmy Dykes' double.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Next inning, Mule Haas tripled with one out and scored on Joe Boley's groundout.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Cochrane's eighth inning home run gave the A's their last run of the game.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] George Earnshaw allowed six hits and walked one, putting the A's ahead 2–0.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The Athletics scored six runs in the first four innings to put the game out of reach.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Mickey Cochrane's two-out home run in the first gave the A's their first run.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] After Al Simmons singled, Jimmie Foxx's RBI double made it 2–0 A's.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] George Watkins's home run in the second gave the Cardinals their only run of the game.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] In the third, Cochrane reached on an error and scored on Simmons's double.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] After an intentional walk, Bing Miller's RBI single made it 4–1 A's.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Philadelphia added two more runs next inning on Jimmy Dykes's double.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] After the A's loaded the bases in the top of the first, Hallahan settled down and pitched a shutout.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Philadelphia left a total of 11 men on base.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The Cardinals scored the game's first run on Taylor Douthit's home run in the fourth, then next inning hit three consecutive one-out singles, the last of which by Charlie Gelbert scoring a run.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] In the seventh, Bill Shores allowed three consecutive leadoff singles, the last of which by Jimmie Wilson scoring two runs.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Next inning, the Cardinals added another run off of Jack Quinn on back-to-back one-out doubles by Jim Bottomley and Chick Hafey.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] An error by Jimmy Dykes in the fourth inning allowed the Cardinals to score two runs.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Haines did not allow a hit after the third inning.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The A's got on the board in the first on Al Simmons's RBI single, but the Cardinals tied the game in the third when Charlie Gelbert tripled and scored on Jesse Haines's single.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] In the fourth, Chick Hafey hit a two-out ground rule double and scored on Dykes's error on Ray Blades's ground ball.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Blades then scored on Gelbert's RBI single.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] George Earnshaw dueled Burleigh Grimes scoreless through seven innings before Lefty Grove took over for Earnshaw in the eighth.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] In the top of the ninth, Grimes walked Mickey Cochrane and then coughed up a home run ball to Jimmie Foxx.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Earnshaw earned his second win on just one day of rest, pitching a five-hitter; it would be 88 years before another pitcher would start consecutive games in the postseason.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Just like in Game 1, the A's seven hits came in five different innings, leading to two runs in the first and fourth innings, and single runs in the third, fifth, and sixth innings.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] As in Game 1, all the A's hits were extra-base hits, including home runs by Al Simmons and Jimmy Dykes.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Although the A's hit only .197 (35–for–178) in the six game set, 18 of their hits went for extra bases, outscoring the Cardinals, 21–12.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Louis only managed a .200 batting average in the series.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The A's struck first in the first on RBI doubles by Mickey Cochrane and Bing Miller, both after walks.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] Simmon's home run in the third off of Syl Johnson made it 3–0 A's, then Dykes's home run after a walk in the fourth increased their lead to 5–0.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The A's added to their lead next inning when Jimmie Foxx hit a leadoff double, moved to third on a bunt groundout and scored on Mule Haas's sacrifice fly. the A's scored their last run of the game in the sixth off of Jim Lindsey on Cochrane's sacrifice fly.
[src:1930-world-series/1930-world-series] The Cardinals scored their only run of the game on Chick Hafey's RBI double in the ninth.
